{"title_page": "2020 24 Hours of Le Mans", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Le Mans Races\n| Previous = 2019\n| Current = 2020\n| Next = 2021\n}}\n[[File:Circuit de la Sarthe track map.svg|thumbnail|right|Circuit de la Sarthe track]]\n\nThe '''88th 24 Hours of Le Mans''' ({{lang-fr|link=no|88<sup>e</sup> 24 Heures du Mans}}) will be an [[endurance racing (motorsport)|automobile endurance event]] at the [[Circuit de la Sarthe]], [[Le Mans]], [[France]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.lemans.org/en/news/the-2020-le-mans-24-hours-will-be-on-13-14-june/49997 | title=The 2020 Le Mans 24 Hours will be on 13\u201314 June! | date=17 August 2018 | accessdate=17 June 2019 | website=Lemans.org}}</ref> It will be the 88th running of the 24 Hour race organised by the [[Automobile Club de l'Ouest]], and the penultimate round of the [[2019\u201320 FIA World Endurance Championship]]. The event is scheduled to be held from 19&ndash;20 September 2020.\n\n==Schedule==\n\n==Entries==\n\n===Automatic entries===\nAutomatic entry invitations were earned by teams that won their class in the 2019 24 Hours of Le Mans, or won championships in the [[European Le Mans Series]], [[Asian Le Mans Series]], and the [[Michelin Le Mans Cup]]. The second-place finishers in the [[European Le Mans Series]] in LMP2 and LMGTE championships also earned an automatic invitation each.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://sportscar365.com/lemans/elms/six-le-mans-auto-invites-granted-after-portimao-weekend/ | title=Six Le Mans Auto Invites Granted After Portimao Weekend | date=28 October 2019 | accessdate=28 October 2019 | website=sportscar365.com}}</ref> Two participants from the [[WeatherTech SportsCar Championship]] were chosen by the series to be automatic entries by the ACO regardless of their performance or category. As invitations were granted to teams, they were allowed to change their cars from the previous year to the next, but not allowed to change their category. The LMGTE class invitations from the European and Asian Le Mans Series were allowed to choose between the Pro and Am categories. European Le Mans Series' LMP3 (Le Mans Prototype 3) champion is required to field an entry in LMP2 while the [[Asian Le Mans Series]] LMP3 champion were permitted to choose between LMP2 or LMGTE Am. The [[2019 Michelin Le Mans Cup|Michelin Le Mans Cup]] [[Group GT3]] (GT3) champion was limited to the LMGTE Am category.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 85%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Reason invited\n! scope=\"col\" | LMP1\n! scope=\"col\" | LMP2\n! scope=\"col\" | LMGTE Pro\n! scope=\"col\" | LMGTE Am\n|-\n| 1st in the [[2019 24 Hours of Le Mans|24 Hours of Le Mans]]\n|{{flagicon|JPN}} [[Toyota Motorsport GmbH|Toyota Gazoo Racing]]\n|{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Signature Team|Signatech Alpine Matmut]]\n|{{flagicon|ITA}} [[AF Corse]]\n|{{flagicon|DEU}} [[Team Project 1]]\n|-\n| 1st in the [[2019 European Le Mans Series|European Le Mans Series]] (LMP2 and LMGTE)\n! rowspan=\"9\" |\n|{{flagicon|FRA}} IDEC Sport\n| colspan=\"2\" |{{flagicon|USA}} Luzich Racing\n|-\n| 2nd in the European Le Mans Series (LMP2 and LMGTE)\n| rowspan=\"1\" |{{flagicon|RUS}} [[TDS Racing|G-Drive Racing]]\n| colspan=\"2\" |{{flagicon|DEU}} [[Patrick Dempsey|Dempsey]]-[[Proton Competition|Proton Racing]]\n|-\n| 1st in the European Le Mans Series (LMP3)\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[EuroInternational]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" |\n! rowspan=\"1\" |\n|-\n|[[WeatherTech SportsCar Championship]] at-large entries\n|{{flagicon|CAN}} Cameron Cassels\n|{{flagicon|USA}} Richard Heistand\n|-\n| 1st in the [[2019\u201320 Asian Le Mans Series|Asian Le Mans Series]] (LMP2 and GT)\n| rowspan=\"1\" |{{flagicon|RUS}} G-Drive Racing with Algarve\n| colspan=\"2\" |{{flagicon|TWN}} HubAuto Corsa\n|-\n| 1st in the Asian Le Mans Series (LMP2 Am)\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Rick Ware Racing]]\n! rowspan=\"1\" |\n! rowspan=\"1\" |\n|-\n| 1st in the Asian Le Mans Series (LMP3)\n|{{flagicon|GBR}} Nielsen Racing\n! align=\"center\" | \u2013 or \