 replace any invitations that were not accepted or withdrawn.  Reserve entries are ordered with the first reserve replacing the first withdrawal from the race, regardless of the class of either entry.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 85%\"\n|-\n! Reserve\n! Class\n! {{Tooltip|No.|Car number}}\n! Entrant\n! Car\n! Tyre\n! Series\n! Driver 1\n! Driver 2\n! Driver 3\n|-\n|align=center| 1st\n|align=center| LMP1\n|align=center| 4\n| {{flagicon|AUT}} [[ByKolles Racing|ByKolles Racing Team]]\n| [[CLM P1/01|ENSO CLM P1/01]]-[[Gibson Technology|Gibson]]\n| {{Michelin}}\n|align=center| '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:red; background-color:#8FCFDF\">24LM</span>'''\n| {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Tom Dillmann]]\n| {{flagicon image|Flag of None.svg}} TBA\n| {{flagicon image|Flag of None.svg}} TBA\n|-\n|align=center| 2nd\n|align=center| LMP2\n|align=center| 17\n| {{flagicon|FRA}} IDEC Sport\n| [[Oreca 07]]-[[Gibson Technology|Gibson]]\n| {{Michelin}}\n|align=center| '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:white; background-color:blue\">ELMS</span>'''\n| {{flagicon|FRA}} Patrice Lafargue\n| {{flagicon image|Flag of None.svg}} TBA\n| {{flagicon image|Flag of None.svg}} TBA\n|-\n|align=center| 3rd\n|align=center| LMP2\n|align=center| 20\n| {{flagicon|DNK}} High Class Racing\n| [[Oreca 07]]-[[Gibson Technology|Gibson]]\n| {{Michelin}}\n|align=center| '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:white; background-color:blue\">ELMS</span>'''\n| {{flagicon|DNK}} [[Jan Magnussen]]\n| {{flagicon image|Flag of None.svg}} TBA\n| {{flagicon image|Flag of None.svg}} TBA\n|-\n|align=center| 4th\n|align=center| LMGTE Am\n|align=center| 78\n| {{flagicon|DEU}} [[Proton Competition]]\n| [[Porsche 911 RSR (2017)|Porsche 911 RSR]]\n| {{Michelin}}\n|align=center| '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:white; background-color:blue\">ELMS</span>'''\n| {{flagicon|NOR}} [[Dennis Olsen (racing driver)|Dennis Olsen]]\n| {{flagicon image|Flag of None.svg}} TBA\n| {{flagicon image|Flag of None.svg}} TBA\n|-\n|align=center| 5th\n|align=center| LMP2\n|align=center| 27\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[DragonSpeed|DragonSpeed USA]]\n| [[Oreca 07]]-[[Gibson Technology|Gibson]]\n| {{Michelin}}\n|align=center| '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:white; background-color:red\">WTSC</span>'''\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Ben Hanley]]\n| {{flagicon|SWE}} Henrik Hedman\n| {{flagicon|SWE}} [[Felix Rosenqvist]]\n|-\n|align=center| 6th\n|align=center| LMGTE Am\n|align=center| 60\n| {{flagicon|ITA}} Iron Lynx\n| [[Ferrari 488 GTE#Ferrari 488 GTE EVO|Ferrari 488 GTE Evo]]\n| {{Michelin}}\n|align=center| '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:white; background-color:blue\">ELMS</span>'''\n| {{flagicon|ITA}} Sergio Pianezzola\n| {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Andrea Piccini]]\n| {{flagicon|ITA}} Claudio Schiavoni\n|-\n|align=center| 7th\n|align=center| LMP2\n|align=center| 23\n| {{flagicon|POL}} Inter Europol Competition\n| [[Ligier JS P217]]-[[Gibson Technology|Gibson]]\n| {{Michelin}}\n|align=center| '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:black; background-color:gold;\">ALMS</span>'''\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Nigel Moore (racing driver)|Nigel Moore]]\n| {{flagicon image|Flag of None.svg}} TBA\n| {{flagicon image|Flag of None.svg}} TBA\n|-\n|align=center| 8th\n|align=center| LMGTE Am\n|align=center| 89\n| {{flagicon|DEU}} [[Team Project 1]]\n| [[Porsche 911 RSR (2017)|Porsche 911 RSR]]\n| {{Michelin}}\n|align=center| '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:red; background-color:#8FCFDF\">24LM</span>'''\n| {{flagicon|DEU}} David Kolkmann\n| {{flagicon image|Flag of None.svg}} TBA\n| {{flagicon image|Flag of None.svg}} TBA\n|-\n|align=center| 9th\n|align=center| LMGTE Am\n|align=center| 96\n| {{flagicon|JPN}} D'station Racing\n| [[Aston Martin Vantage GTE (2018)|Aston Martin Vantage AMR]]\n| {{Michelin}}\n|align=center| '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:black; background-color:gold;\">ALMS</span>'''\n| {{flagicon|JPN}} [[Tomonobu Fujii]]\n| {{flagicon|JPN}} Satoshi Hoshino\n| {{flagicon image|Flag of None.svg}} TBA\n|-\n|}\n\n==Qualifying==\n===Hyperpole - New Qualifying Format=== \nIn the new qualifying format, after the first qualifying session on Wednesday night, the 6 cars from each of the 4 classes (24 cars) with best lap times will compete in a second qualifying session on Thursday night called \"Le Mans Hyperpole\".  Previously, Le Mans qualifying consisted of three (3) qualifying sessions.  \n<ref>{{cite web |last1=Watkins |first1=Gary |title=New 'Hyperpole' Le Mans 24 Hours qualifying format to be introduced |url=https://www.autosport.com/wec/news/147671/le-mans-24-hours-qualifying-format-changed |website=autosport.com |accessdate=22 January 2020 |date=18 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Starting Grid - by Class===\nCars will be placed on the starting grid, first by category / class order: \n# LMP1\n# LMP2\n# LMGTE Pro\n# LMGTE Am\nThen, within each of the categories above,  the cars will be placed in following order: the 6 cars that qualified for Hyperpole by best Hyperpole session lap time, and then followed by the rest of the cars in the class that did not qualify for Hyperpole by best lap time set during first qualifying session.<ref>{{cite web |title=2020 24 Hours of Le Mans Supplementary Regulations - version 1 |url=https://assets.lemans.org/explorer/pdf/courses/2020/24-heures-du-mans/regulations/2020-24-heures-du-mans-supplementary-regulations.pdf |website=ACO |accessdate=22 January 2020 |date=18 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[2020 Road to Le Mans]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- {{Commons category|2020 24 Hours of Le Mans}} -->\n* {{official website|http://www.24h-lemans.com/}}\n\n{{Sportscar Race Report\n|Year_of_race=2019\u201320\n|Sportscar_Series=FIA World Endurance Championship\n|Previous_race_in_season=[[2020 6 Hours of Spa-Francorchamps|6 Hours of Spa-Francorchamps]]\n|Next_race_in_season=none\n}}\n{{WEC Rounds}}\n{{24 Hours of Le Mans}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:24 Hours of Le Mans, 2020}}\n[[Category:24 Hours of Le Mans races|2020]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 FIA World Endurance Championship season|Le Man]]\n[[Category:2020 in motorsport|Le Mans]]\n[[Category:2020 in French sport|Le Mans]]\n[[Category:September 2020 sports events in France]]\n[[Category:Scheduled sports events]]\n[[Category:Motorsport events postponed due to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|24 Hours of Le Mans]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Le Mans Races\n| Previous = 2019\n| Current = 2020\n| Next = 2021\n}}\n[[File:Circuit de la Sarthe track map.svg|thumbnail|right|Circuit de la Sarthe track]]\n\nThe '''88th 24 Hours of Le Mans''' ({{lang-fr|link=no|88<sup>e</sup> 24 Heures du Mans}}) will be an [[endurance racing (motorsport)|automobile endurance event]] at the [[Circuit de la Sarthe]], [[Le Mans]], [[France]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.lemans.org/en/news/the-2020-le-mans-24-hours-will-be-on-13-14-june/49997 | title=The 2020 Le Mans 24 Hours will be on 13\u201314 June! | date=17 August 2018 | accessdate=17 June 2019 | website=Lemans.org}}</ref> It will be the 88th running of the 24 Hour race organised by the [[Automobile Club de l'Ouest]], and the penultimate round of the [[2019\u201320 FIA World Endurance Championship]]. The event is scheduled to be held from 19&ndash;20 September 2020.\n\n==Schedule==\n\n==Entries==\n\n===Automatic entries===\nAutomatic entry invitations were earned by teams that won their class in the 2019 24 Hours of Le Mans, or won championships in the [[European Le Mans Series]], [[Asian Le Mans Series]], and the [[Michelin Le Mans Cup]]. The second-place finishers in the [[European Le Mans Series]] in LMP2 and LMGTE championships also earned an automatic invitation each.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://sportscar365.com/lemans/elms/six-le-mans-auto-invites-granted-after-portimao-weekend/ | title=Six Le Mans Auto Invites Granted After Portimao Weekend | date=28 October 2019 | accessdate=28 October 2019 | website=sportscar365.com}}</ref> Two participants from the [[WeatherTech SportsCar Championship]] were chosen by the series to be automatic entries by the ACO regardless of their performance or category. As invitations were granted to teams, they were allowed to change their cars from the previous year to the next, but not allowed to change their category. The LMGTE class invitations from the European and Asian Le Mans Series were allowed to choose between the Pro and Am categories. European Le Mans Series' LMP3 (Le Mans Prototype 3) champion is required to field an entry in LMP2 while the [[Asian Le Mans Series]] LMP3 champion were permitted to choose between LMP2 or LMGTE Am. The [[2019 Michelin Le Mans Cup|Michelin Le Mans Cup]] [[Group GT3]] (GT3) champion was limited to the LMGTE Am category.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 85%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Reason invited\n! scope=\"col\" | LMP1\n! scope=\"col\" | LMP2\n! scope=\"col\" | LMGTE Pro\n! scope=\"col\" | LMGTE Am\n|-\n| 1st in the [[2019 24 Hours of Le Mans|24 Hours of Le Mans]]\n|{{flagicon|JPN}} [[Toyota Motorsport GmbH|Toyota Gazoo Racing]]\n|{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Signature Team|Signatech Alpine Matmut]]\n|{{flagicon|ITA}} [[AF Corse]]\n|{{flagicon|DEU}} [[Team Project 1]]\n|-\n| 1st in the [[2019 European Le Mans Series|European Le Mans Series]] (LMP2 and LMGTE)\n! rowspan=\"9\" |\n|{{flagicon|FRA}} IDEC Sport\n| colspan=\"2\" |{{flagicon|USA}} Luzich Racing\n|-\n| 2nd in the European Le Mans Series (LMP2 and LMGTE)\n| rowspan=\"1\" |{{flagicon|RUS}} [[TDS Racing|G-Drive Racing]]\n| colspan=\"2\" |{{flagicon|DEU}} [[Patrick Dempsey|Dempsey]]-[[Proton Competition|Proton Racing]]\n|-\n| 1st in the European Le Mans Series (LMP3)\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[EuroInternational]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" |\n! rowspan=\"1\" |\n|-\n|[[WeatherTech SportsCar Championship]] at-large entries\n|{{flagicon|CAN}} Cameron Cassels\n|{{flagicon|USA}} Richard Heistand\n|-\n| 1st in the [[2019\u201320 Asian Le Mans Series|Asian Le Mans Series]] (LMP2 and GT)\n| rowspan=\"1\" |{{flagicon|RUS}} G-Drive Racing with Algarve\n| colspan=\"2\" |{{flagicon|TWN}} HubAuto Corsa\n|-\n| 1st in the Asian Le Mans Series (LMP2 Am)\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Rick Ware Racing]]\n! rowspan=\"1\" |\n! rowspan=\"1\" |\n|-\n| 1st in the Asian Le Mans Series (LMP3)\n|{{flagicon|GBR}} Nielsen Racing\n! align=\"center\" | \u2013 or \u2013\n|{{flagicon|GBR}} Nielsen Racing\n|-\n| 1st in the Michelin Le Mans Cup (GT3)\n! rowspan=\"2\" |\n! rowspan=\"3\" |\n| colspan=\"1\" |{{flagicon|CHE}} [[Loris Kessel|Kessel Racing]]\n|}\n\n===Entry list===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 85%;\"\n! Icon\n! Series\n|-\n|align=center| '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:white; background-color:green;\">WEC</span>'''\n| FIA World Endurance Championship\n|-\n|align=center| '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:white; background-color:blue\">ELMS</span>'''\n| European Le Mans Series\n|-\n|align=center| '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:black; background-color:gold;\">ALMS</span>'''\n| Asian Le Mans Series\n|-\n|align=center| '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:white; background-color:red\">WTSC</span>'''\n| WeatherTech SportsCar Championship\n|-\n|align=center| '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:red; background-color:#8FCFDF\">24LM</span>'''\n| 24 Hours of Le Mans only\n|-\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 85%\"\n|-\n! {{Tooltip|No.|Car number}}\n! Entrant\n! Car\n! Tyre\n! Series\n! Driver 1\n! Driver 2\n! Driver 3\n|-\n! colspan=8| LMP1 (6 entries)\n|-\n|align=center| 1\n| {{flagicon|CHE}} [[Rebellion Racing]]\n| [[Rebellion R13]]-[[Gibson Technology|Gibson]]\n| {{Michelin}}\n|align=center|  '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:white; background-color:green;\">WEC</span>'''\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Gustavo Menezes]]\n| {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Norman Nato]]\n| {{flagicon|BRA}} [[Bruno Senna]]\n|-\n|align=center| 3\n| {{flagicon|CHE}} [[Rebellion Racing]]\n| [[Rebellion R13]]-[[Gibson Technology|Gibson]]\n| {{Michelin}}\n|align=center| '''<span