ames#Scripting|Zillions Rules]]\n| {{No}}\n| 2D\n| [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]]\n| \n| {{proprietary}}\n| \n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! style=\"width: 12em\" | Name\n! Primary programming language\n! Scripting\n! Cross-platform\n! 2D/3D oriented\n! Target platform\n! Notable games\n! License\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes and references\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Physics engine]]\n* [[Game engine recreation]]\n* [[List of open-source video games]]\n* [[List of WebGL frameworks]]\n* [[Role-playing game creation software]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Video game engines}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Game engines}}\n[[Category:Video game engines| ]]\n[[Category:Technology-related lists]]\n", "name_user": "Krestenlaust", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added Terraria as a notable game", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_game_engines"}
{"title_page": "Josephine Weiss", "text_new": "'''Josephine Weiss''' (1805 - 1852) was an Austrian ballet dancer and dance troupe leader who travelled Europe and the United States with her team of young girls, Les Danseuses Viennoises (\"the Viennoise Children\").<ref>The Literary Gazette and Journal of the Belles Lettres, Arts, Sciences, 1842</ref>   \n\n== Early Life ==\nWeiss was born in Austria in 1805. She spent much of her early life dancing for various Austrian ballet companies, including the [[K\u00e4rntnertor Theater]] in [[Vienna]], where she was a soloist from 1820 to 1826.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/oi/authority.20110803121623638|title=Josephine Weiss|website=Oxford Reference|language=en|doi=10.1093/oi/authority.20110803121623638|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> Whilst there, she met and married Eduard Weiss, a comic actor.<ref name=\"auto\">To-day, Volume 2, 1852 by Charles Hale p123</ref> \n\n== Career ==\nBy 1844 Weiss had been appointed as a ballet mistress for the Josephsst\u00e4dter Theater and had formed her own troupe of young girls \u2013 Les Danseuses Viennoises.<ref>The Illustrated London News, Volume 6, 1845</ref> The dancers were aged between five and twelve years old, and under the guidance of Weiss the troupe toured Europe widely, and were even watched by Queen Victoria in London.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rct.uk/collection/980011-v|title=Queen Victoria, Queen of the United Kingdom (1819-1901) - The Viennoises|website=www.rct.uk}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>Great Ballet Prints of the Romantic Era by By Parmenia Migel</ref> In November and December 1844 the troupe performed at The Royal Dutch Theatre at [[The Hague]] in the Netherlands, however local newspapers expressed concern that such young children were being trained for stage performances.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Aage Gillhoff|first=Gerd|title=The Royal Dutch Theatre at the Hague 1804\u20131876|publisher=Springer|year=2013|isbn=|location=|pages=142}}</ref>\n\nIn 1846 Weiss arranged a tour to the United States and on 22 September they boarded the [[SS Great Britain]] in [[Liverpool]] headed for [[New York City|New York]]. One day into the journey, however, the ship ran ashore in [[Dundrum Bay]] in [[Northern Ireland]]. Other passengers recalled the event in diaries, with one writing that \u2018the Viennese children kept crying violently around Madame Weiss\u2019. The troupe were collected by ships and returned to Liverpool the following day, where they were asked to perform at the Royal Adelphi Theater.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalstories.ssgreatbritain.org/_/traveller/454|title=SS Great Britain : Brunel's ss Great Britain|website=globalstories.ssgreatbritain.org}}</ref> The troupe eventually did make the journey to the United States, and performed in Philadelphia, New York City, St. Louis, Mobile and New Orleans between November 1846 and February 1847 under the name \"the Viennoise Children\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Brodsky Lawrence|first=Vera|title=Strong on Music: The New York Music Scene in the Days of George Templeton Strong, Volume 1: Resonances, 1836-1849|publisher=University of Chicago Press|year=1995|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Miller Ludlow|first=Noah|title=Dramatic Life as I Found it: A Record of Personal Experience ; with an Account of the Rise and Progress of the Drama in the West and South, with Anecdotes and Biographical Sketches of the Principal Actors and Actresses who Have at Times Appeared Upon the Stage in the Mississippi Valley|publisher=G.I. Jones and Company|year=1880|isbn=|location=|pages=668}}</ref> In April 1848 they performed a second season in St. Louis.<ref name=\":2\" /> On several occasions during preparations for performances in the south of the United States, it was noted by observers that Weiss was often angry with the children and swore at them in both German and English, causing some to approach her and ask her to moderate her language.<ref name=\":2\" /> In 1848, the troupe was closed down due to moral objections.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=The Oxford Dictionary of Dance|publisher=OUP Oxford|year=2010|isbn=|location=Oxford, England|pages=121}}</ref>\n\nLater in her career, Weiss taught ballet at the National Ballet Theatre School in [[Zagreb]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Death ==\nJosephine Weiss died suddenly on 18 December 1852\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1805 births]]\n[[Category:1852 deaths]]\n[[Category:Austrian ballet dancers]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weiss, Josephine}}\n{{Authority control}}\n", "text_old": "'''Josephine Weiss''' (1805 - 1852) was an Austrian ballet dancer and dance troupe leader who travelled Europe and the United States with her team of young girls, Les Danseuses Viennoises (\"the Viennoise Children\").<ref>The Literary Gazette and Journal of the Belles Lettres, Arts, Sciences, 1842</ref>   \n\n== Early Life ==\nWeiss was born in Austria in 1805. She spent much of her early life dancing for various Austrian ballet companies, including the [[K\u00e4rntnertor Theater]] in [[Vienna]], where she was a soloist from 1820 to 1826.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/oi/authority.20110803121623638|title=Josephine Weiss|website=Oxford Reference|language=en|doi=10.1093/oi/authority.20110803121623638|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> Whilst there, she met and married Eduard Weiss, a comic actor.<ref name=\"auto\">To-day, Volume 2, 1852 by Charles Hale p123</ref> \n\n== Career ==\nBy 1844 Weiss had been appointed as a ballet mistress for the Josephsst\u00e4dter Theater and had formed her own troupe of young girls \u2013 Les Danseuses Viennoises.<ref>The Illustrated London News, Volume 6, 1845</ref> The dancers were aged between five and twelve years old, and under the guidance of Weiss the troupe toured Europe widely, and were even watched by Queen Victoria in London.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rct.uk/collection/980011-v|title=Queen Victoria, Queen of the United Kingdom (1819-1901) - The Viennoises|website=www.rct.uk}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>Great Ballet Prints of the Romantic Era by By Parmenia Migel</ref> In November and December 1844 the troupe performed at The Royal Dutch Theatre at [[The Hague]] in the Netherlands, however local newspapers expressed concern that such young children were being trained for stage performances.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Aage Gillhoff|first=Gerd|title=The Royal Dutch Theatre at the Hague 1804\u20131876|publisher=Springer|year=2013|isbn=|location=|pages=142}}</ref>\n\nIn 1846 Weiss arranged a tour to the United States and on 22 September they boarded the [[SS Great Britain]] in [[Liverpool]] headed for [[New York]]. One day into the journey, however, the ship ran ashore in [[Dundrum Bay]] in [[Northern Ireland]]. Other passengers recalled the event in diaries, with one writing that \u2018the Viennese children kept crying violently around Madame Weiss\u2019. The troupe were collected by ships and returned to Liverpool the following day, where they were asked to perform at the Royal Adelphi Theater.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalstories.ssgreatbritain.org/_/traveller/454|title=SS Great Britain : Brunel's ss Great Britain|website=globalstories.ssgreatbritain.org}}</ref> The troupe eventually did make the journey to the United States, and performed in Philadelphia, New York City, St. Louis, Mobile and New Orleans between November 1846 and February 1847 under the name \"the Viennoise Children\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Brodsky Lawrence|first=Vera|title=Strong on Music: The New York Music Scene in the Days of George Templeton Strong, Volume 1: Resonances, 1836-1849|publisher=University of Chicago Press|year=1995|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Miller Ludlow|first=Noah|title=Dramatic Life as I Found it: A Record of Personal Experience ; with an Account of the Rise and Progress of the Drama in the West and South, with Anecdotes and Biographical Sketches of the Principal Actors and Actresses who Have at Times Appeared Upon the Stage in the Mississippi Valley|publisher=G.I. Jones and Company|year=1880|isbn=|location=|pages=668}}</ref> In April 1848 they performed a second season in St. Louis.<ref name=\":2\" /> On several occasions during preparations for performances in the south of the United States, it was noted by observers that Weiss was often angry with the children and swore at them in both German and English, causing some to approach her and ask her to moderate her language.<ref name=\":2\" /> In 1848, the troupe was closed down due to moral objections.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=The Oxford Dictionary of Dance|publisher=OUP Oxford|year=2010|isbn=|location=Oxford, England|pages=121}}</ref>\n\nLater in her career, Weiss taught ballet at the National Ballet Theatre School in [[Zagreb]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Death ==\nJosephine Weiss died suddenly on 18 December 1852\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1805 births]]\n[[Category:1852 deaths]]\n[[Category:Austrian ballet dancers]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weiss, Josephine}}\n{{Authority control}}\n", "name_user": "R'n'B", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toNew York(link changed toNew York City) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Josephine_Weiss"}
